Then explain:

Only about 38% of passengers survived the Titanic disaster.

Chapter 2: Did Gender Matter?
sns.countplot(data=df, x='sex', hue='survived')
plt.title('Survival by Gender')
plt.show()

Story:

Women were far more likely to survive than men, reflecting the "women and children first" evacuation policy.

Chapter 3: Did Wealth Matter?
sns.countplot(data=df, x='pclass', hue='survived')
plt.title('Survival by Passenger Class')
plt.show()

Story:

First-class passengers had significantly higher survival rates than third-class passengers.

Chapter 4: Did Age Matter?
sns.histplot(df['age'], bins=30, kde=True)
plt.title('Age Distribution')
plt.show()

Story:

Most passengers were young adults, but children often had better survival chances.

Chapter 5: The Cost of Survival
sns.boxplot(data=df, x='survived', y='fare')
plt.title('Fare vs Survival')
plt.show()

Story:

Passengers paying higher fares generally had better access to lifeboats and survival opportunities.

Final Dashboard

Instead of 10 separate charts, create 4 key charts arranged together:

fig, axes = plt.subplots(2,2, figsize=(14,10))

sns.countplot(data=df, x='survived', ax=axes[0,0])
axes[0,0].set_title("Overall Survival")

sns.countplot(data=df, x='sex', hue='survived', ax=axes[0,1])
axes[0,1].set_title("Gender Impact")

sns.countplot(data=df, x='pclass', hue='survived', ax=axes[1,0])
axes[1,0].set_title("Class Impact")

sns.boxplot(data=df, x='survived', y='fare', ax=axes[1,1])
axes[1,1].set_title("Fare Impact")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()
